segments.text: This is July 10.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: I'm at 204 Redmond getting ready to talk to one of the distinguished professors retired in veterinary medicine, Professor Callaham.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: Now, let's say a sentence and let's check yours.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: All right.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: I'll say a small sentence right now until you get lined out on something else.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: To begin with,
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: For the sake of someone who might listen to this tape or read the transcription 20 or 30 years from now and might not know your background, describe where you grew up, what your family did, where they lived, and how long they lived there.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: All right.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: I was born and raised in the panhandle of Texas out east of Amarillo, Carson County, community there, and my family were, we lived on a farm and ranch combination, ran probably between 2,400 and 4,000 acres, about half
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: tilled row crop wheat and the other half grass.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: I was born in 1919, so you can figure out right quick that my teen, my late preteens and my teenage years growing up were during the Depression days and also during the Dust Bowl days, which were very simultaneous, particularly in that part of the, in the country, and we did not have irrigation at that time.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: uh i went to a a school at the time i started the school was a little little community school in conway texas and it was a three-room schoolhouse and they taught through the 10th grade in that three rooms
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: which sounds horrible, but at the time, being small like that wasn't altogether bad.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: Now it would be tragic, of course.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: my two older sisters skipped their senior year of school because otherwise they would have had to go to Claude or Panhandle nearby schools.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: But they took entrance examinations for West Texas State and were admitted, and both of them were honor students, made dean's list, et cetera, and so forth.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: I went there through my sophomore, no, through my freshman year, through the eighth grade, to this country school, three rooms.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: And I think sometimes people don't realize that the little ones learn from the big ones.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: You're all in the same room.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: And which means, of course, too, the homework was a very important part of your education because you got assignment.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: Anyway, through my eighth grade, I went to that school.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: Then I had two sisters and a brother who were college age, and they needed to go to college.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: And the only way we could do it at that time was for my parents to rent a house over in Canyon, near the West Texas State at that time.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: So my dad stayed on the farm and we moved the rest of the family to Canyon in a house large enough to accommodate four guys' room and board.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: And my mother had very little help except for my older sisters and me and my brother, which didn't amount to much around the house.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: But anyway, we made it.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: So your mother...
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: was the boarding house lady.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: Yes.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: But you all kept the farm.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: Right.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: And what was the money crop out on the farm and ranch?
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: Wheat, row crop, milo, high gear, and cattle.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: And in the old days, that wasn't much.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: We hired, sometimes we hired hired hands that got $30 a month in their room and board.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: and they made more money than my dad did because he didn't make anything some years.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: In fact, there was a time when he had every dollar borrowed that he could borrow on his insurance, land, cattle, automobiles, whatever.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: and it got that sticky because we didn't know it at the time and we were better off than most, most of the people around us because we had garden and we had stock, we had chickens and we ate real well and even though we wear patch clothes, we didn't know that wasn't normal.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: So anyway, we went, I went to high school in N.N.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: Canyon for my sophomore year
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: And I wasn't eligible for athletics, being that my first year there.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: But the next year, my mother moved back to the country.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: She didn't come back for the next school year.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: But I was eligible for football in Canyon, Texas.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: And very stupidly, that was a big deal.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: So the former students and townspeople rented a little house, had a big bedroom, living room combination and a kitchen and a place you could eat in it, in the bathroom, for me and another kid so we could play football, which was, I guess, illegal at the time, but nobody paid much attention to that.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: And I wasn't all that good, but then like a lot of other things that you fall into, they needed a body or something.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: Somebody with legs and hands and legs.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: Anyway, that worked out pretty well until football season was over, and then at midterm of our high school year, I moved in with my grandmother who lived in Canyon, and she kept borders, and my brothers and sisters had stayed with her at one time or another.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: So I went in the last two years then, or a year and a half, living during the school year with my grandmother and then going back home to Conway to the farm in the summertime.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: How many in your senior class?
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: Do you remember in high school?
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: We graduated, there was about 37 of us graduated from high school my senior year.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: And in athletics y'all played what other towns?
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: We played Tulia, Perryton, Panhandle, Hereford, and let's see, Freona went basketball, but not football.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: We had mediocre football teams, had good basketball teams, played all over the Panhandle.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: We went to district sailing through.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: One year, my junior year, we ran into a little team from down close to Lubbock, a little country school.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: In that day and time, I might add, if I hadn't already mentioned it,
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: You had A and B classifications.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: That was it.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: And that was a big school.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: Like Amarillo was A and B. You all were B. And we could beat them in basketball, but we didn't play them in football.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: Anyway, this time I lost my train of thought there.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: Well, in terms of college,
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: When did you begin to think about going to college and where?
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: Okay, I cannot even remember when I didn't intend to go to college.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: Of course, when you think of the times then, you're reminded that I graduated in high school in 1937, the depths of a depression.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: But I intended to go to college for as long as I could remember.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: Going to A&M was something that started early, fairly early in high school.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: I had a cousin that was here.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: Of course, I'd heard of its reputation.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: And then a county agent was influential.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: Then when I went to high school, my vocational ag teacher, he was not a graduate of A&M, had no connection to it.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: But we became fairly close as much as a coach and a teacher could be, and he was very insistent that I come to A&M.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: So eventually, probably he was the most influential.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: Did you come to visit before you came to enroll?
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: No.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: I had never been here before.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: I had been to Texas Tech to their judging contests and so forth, their ag school put on down there, but I had never been to A&M before.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: Do you remember how you applied and about when?
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: I was very late in applying.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: The exact date I have no recollection, but it was very late and I could not get in the dormitory.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: So— First of all, how did you get down here, though?
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: How did you get here physically?
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: My parents—I had a sister teaching school down on the Rio Grande River in South Texas, and my folks were going to visit her.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: So they brought me down here in the car with one lousy little suitcase, had two sheets in it and a change of clothes,
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: and dropped me off in front of the old YMCA building and said good luck and goodbye, and we'll hope to see you soon.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: Do you remember how much money you had at your disposal?
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: I had a few dollars, but I had a—my dad told me, he said, Now, son, you know what the situation is.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: We don't have money.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: speak of, very little.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: And I had enough money.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: No, I didn't.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: I probably had $10 in my pocket at the most.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: But he said, you can write checks, but be very careful so you know what the deal is.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: He said, sign my name, and then under that, you sign yours for what you have to have.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: And that was it.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: and I knew that I didn't have a job, and I knew I had to work, stay in school.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: I could probably go out and wait until Christmas, but maybe go a year and drop out a year and work and then come back.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: But they dropped me off there, and I got out of the car, and it was hot, dry, and I saw this fountain up on the
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: veranda of the YMCA building, big old crock fountain, stone fountain, and I'll never forget that.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: I went there and, man, that big old stream of water came out of that dude, and what I hadn't noticed at the time was that yellow-greenish stuff in the bottom of that old deal.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: But I took a great big swig of that water and then took a breath and I almost vomited right there on the deal.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: That was almost pure sulfur.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: It was not totally sulfur, but it was still liquid.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: But that's one of the little things that I come along that you remember.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: But anyway, I had no place to stay that night.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: I didn't have a room or anything.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: Got ahold of this cousin of mine eventually and he said, well, find an empty room in a dorm somewhere and then we can see about getting a place to stay tomorrow.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: So I went over to Law Hall and there was an open place with double bunks and I got out my seats, took them on the bed and spent the night there.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: And the next day I found this place in Bryan that was owned by former Senator Gaynor.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: And he had this big two-story, pretty big two-story house down by the railroad tracks on the west side.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: And so they kept rumors but not borders.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: And I guess there were eight of us there in these
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: upstairs bedrooms.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: And there was a boarding house in Bryan at that time where we could go and get a meal, whichever one.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: And I think breakfast was two bits and lunch fits sense, as I recall.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: If you eat lunch, I can't remember about dinner.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: There's probably more, but we make out wherever we could.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: Well, not being in a dormitory, you were referred to as a day dodger.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: And that was because you were dodging the paddles that you had in the organizations.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: That was not true.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: I guarantee you.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: The worst beatings I ever took was in that...
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: where you had upperclassmen who were not regulated by anything or anybody.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: Oh, so there were some upperclass day dodgers at the boarding house?
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: You bet.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: Uh-huh.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: And whether they'd been in a dorm or not, I think there were just two or three of us freshmen.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: There were more upperclassmen than there were freshmen, and that was unfortunate too.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: I guess just over a period of time, gradually.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: I was in headquarters troop in the cavalry.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: It was just named headquarters.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: But there was no number to it, as far as I know.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: We had two day-to-day troops in the cavalry.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: Let's see, we had that one, and I can't remember the name of the other one.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: How did it, how did you get to be in the cavalry?
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: How, why that?
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: I just applied for it.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: Oh, okay.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: When I came to school, I applied for the cavalry, you know, you had to, coming off a ranch, you had to get on the horses, whatever you could.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: So it was the horse part that appealed to you?
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: Oh yeah, just, and it was just something of that nature that appealed to me.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: At that time, you know, you, you, in retrospect,
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: You know, I don't even know why, but it made sense at that particular time.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: How did you register for courses and select those?
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: Okay.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: I was an animal science major.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: We took the same courses at that stage of the game.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: Well this went on also with the same procedure occurred for our second semester.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: And it was a pretty much, very much cut and dried situation and fall in and follow me.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: What time did you get up?
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: What did you do when?
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: And take me from wake up to going to sleep.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: Okay.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.text: Since you were in uniform, as you know, it was not a big chore.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01

segments.speaker: SPEAKER_01
